#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid "Live patching on &slema;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:35
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only the currently running processes are affected by the live patches. As "
"the libraries are changed in the new snapshot and <emphasis role=\"bold"
"\">not</emphasis> in the current one, new processes started in the current "
"snapshot still use the non-patched libraries until you reboot. After the "
"reboot, the system switches to the new snapshot and all started processes "
"will use the patched libraries."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:40
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"User space live patching (&ulpa;) refers to the process of applying patches "
"to the libraries used by a running process, without interrupting it. Live "
"patching operations are performed using the <systemitem>ulp</systemitem> "
"tool that is part of the <systemitem>libpulp</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:47
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem>libpulp</systemitem> is a framework that enables &ulp;. It "
"consists of the <systemitem>libpulp.so</systemitem> library and tools for "
"making libraries live-patchable and applying live patches (the "
"<systemitem>ulp</systemitem> binary)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:55
#, no-c-format
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:56
#, no-c-format
msgid "For &ulpa; to work, two requirements must be met."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:64
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;transactional-update pkg in libpulp0 libpulp-tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:65
#, no-c-format
msgid "After successful installation, reboot your system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:70
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the &ulpa; on your system by running:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:73
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper in libpulp0 libpulp-tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:76
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To be live-patchable, a library must be compiled with the <option>-"
"fpatchable-function-entry</option> GCC flag. No changes to the library "
"source code are required."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:83
#, no-c-format
msgid "Processes must preload the <systemitem>libpulp.so</systemitem> library."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:91
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using libpulp"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:92
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To use <systemitem>libpulp</systemitem> with an application, you must "
"perform the following steps:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:98
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make a library live-patchable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:103
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When launching the application, preload <systemitem>libpulp</systemitem> "
"with the <command>LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib64/libpulp.so ./"
"<replaceable>APPLICATION</replaceable></command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:111
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preparing a library to be live-patchable"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:112
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a library to be live-patchable, it must contain a <literal>NOP</literal> "
"prologue in all function calls. GCC version 8 and higher, as well as the GCC "
"version that ships with &sls;, provides the <option>-fpatchable-function-"
"entry</option> specifically for that purpose. Thus, on the &x86-64; "
"architecture, compiling a library written in C with <option>-fpatchable-"
"function-entry=16,14</option> flag is sufficient to make it live-patchable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:121
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The libraries provided by the system packages glibc and openssl "
"(libopenssl_1_1) are already live-patchable on &productnameshort; "
"&productnumber;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid "Checking if a library is live-patchable"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:128
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To check whether a library is live-patchable, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:131
#, no-c-format
msgid "ulp livepatchable <replaceable>LIBRARY</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:134
#, no-c-format
msgid "Checking if a <filename>.so</filename> file is a live patch container"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:135
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A shared object ( <filename>.so</filename> ) is a live patch container if it "
"contains the ULP patch description embedded into it. You can verify it with "
"the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;readelf -S <replaceable>SHARED_OBJECT</replaceable> | grep .ulp"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:141
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the output shows that there are both <literal>.ulp</literal> and "
"<literal>.ulp.rev</literal> sections in the shared object, then it is a live "
"patch container."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:148
#, no-c-format
msgid "Applying live patches"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:149
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Live patches are applied using the <systemitem>ulp trigger</systemitem> "
"command, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:153
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"ulp trigger -p <replaceable>PID</replaceable> <replaceable>LIVEPATCH</"
"replaceable>.ulp"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:154
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In this example, <literal>PID</literal> is the PID of the running process "
"that uses the library to be patched and <literal>LIVEPATCH.ulp</literal> is "
"the actual live patch file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:159
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>live patching succeeded</literal> message indicates that the "
"live-patching operation was successful."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is also possible to apply multiple live patches by using wildcards. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:167
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;ulp trigger -p <replaceable>PID</replaceable> '*.so'"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This command will try to apply every patch in the current folder to the "
"process holding <literal>PID</literal> . In the end, the tool will show how "
"many patches it successfully applied."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ulp.xml:175
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reverting live patches"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:176
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>ulp trigger</command> can be used to revert live patches. There are "
"two ways to revert live patches. You can revert a live patch by using the "
"<option>--revert</option> switch and passing the live patch container:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;ulp trigger -p <replaceable>PID</replaceable> --revert "
"<replaceable>LIVEPATCH</replaceable>.so"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Alternatively, it is possible to remove all patches associated with a "
"particular library. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:186
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"ulp trigger -p <replaceable>PID</replaceable> --revert-"
"all=<replaceable>LIBRARY</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:187
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In the example above, <replaceable>LIBRARY</replaceable> refers to the "
"actual library, for example: <systemitem>libcrypto.so.1.1</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ulp.xml:191
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The latter approach can be useful when the source code of the original live "
"patch is not available, or you want to remove a specific old patch and apply "
"a new one, without the target application running potentially unsecured "
"code. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ulp.xml:197
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;ulp trigger -p <replaceable>PID</replaceable>  --revert-"
"all=libcrypto.so.1.1 new_livepatch2.so"
msgstr ""

